[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\S. East leads the \DQ.  

Unless East is real beginner West will hold the \DA so you should not try the \DK on this trick. And when East continues with the \DJ you should again duck in dummy, ruffing with an honor in your hand.

The contract is in danger if West holds the \CA because you would have three \C losers to go with the \D already lost. One really good possibility is that West now has the lone \DA and you can set up dummy's \DK with a ruff.

So play a small \S to dummy's \S9, (pulling the two outstanding trumps), and ruff another \D with an honor, hoping the \DA drops.

Too bad, the \DA did not fall so dummy's \DK is not a winner. But it will still prove to be useful. 

Play the \HA, then ruff a \H in dummy. Play a trump to your \SA and ruff your last \H.

You are in dummy, just where you want to be. Play the \DK, and when West plays the \DA don't ruff but instead discard a \C from your hand. You knew all along that he held the \DA.

[showcards N:SJ,CK,C5,C3 S:S6,S3,C7,C6]

West is end-played, forced to either break the \Cs and give you a \C trick, or give you a ruff-sluff.

This was the toughest hand so far and the end-play depended upon your correct reading that West must hold the \DA.

It also depended upon the defenders not switching to \Cs at the second trick. If East had decided to switch to the \CQ you would have had no chance at all. }
[Play "W"]DQ

